2003-05-30  Christian Melsheimer  <melsheimer@uni-bremen.de>

	* arts-1-0-82
	
	* aii/plot_abs_per_tg_2.pro: In line 100, replaced jobdir+jobname
	by jobdirname, otherwise you get an error if the keyword jobname
	is not set.
	
	Set outdir to current working dir in absence of keyword jobdir.

	Added missing initialisation of string_title_T to empty string.

	Corrected bug in scaling of y-axis (... * absscale)
	
	* doc/uguide/absorption.tex: Fixed typos in equations
	eq:comp_perm_lwc (complex permittivity of suspended water
	droplets), and eq:comp_perm_iwc_a (parameter a in complex
	permitt. of ice crystals).

	* src/continua.cc: 
	Created function MPM93RainExt to include parameterization of
	extinction by rain. It is formally based on the functions
	absorption by suspended water droplets (MPM93WaterDropletAbs) and
	ice crystals (MPM93IceCrystalAbs). All three functions are
	formally treated as a special case of water vapour continuum absorption, but
	the volume mixing ratio vmr has the meaning of a rain rate in
	MPM93 RainExt, and of liquid or ice water content in
	MPM93WaterDropletAbs and MPM93IceCrystalAbs.  The parameterization
	of the rain extinction is based on a paper by Olsen, R.L.,
	D.V. Rogers, and D. B. Hodge, "The aR^b relation in the
	calculation of rain attenuation", IEEE Trans. Antennas Propagat.,
	vol. AP-26, pp. 318-329, 1978, and part of it is also in the
	original MPM93 model source code by Liebe et al.
	Note that this is EXTINCTION by rain, not just ABSORPTION, so it
	is not appropriate for the calculation of thermal emission by
	rain!
		
	* src/continua.cc (xsec_continuum_tag): Added "rain-MPM93" and
	relevant information and parameter check.
	
	* src/continua.h: Added the prototype of the new function MPM93RainExt

	* src/partition_function_data.cc (define_partition_species_data):
	Added record for "rain"

	* src/species_data.cc (define_basic_species_data): Added record
	"rain" (which, by the way, has neither degrees of freedom nor isotopes)
 
	* src/workspace.cc (define_wsv_data): Added information about rain
	extinction parameterization.

